data.content:
Three things break. Here's each one with the fix:

---

### 1. `ExecuteUpdateAsync` — expression tree no longer compiles

EF Core 10 changed the parameter from `Expression<Func<…>>` to `Func<…>`, so manual expression-tree construction won't compile. The fix is dramatically simpler:

```csharp
await context.Blogs.ExecuteUpdateAsync(s =>
{
    s.SetProperty(b => b.Views, 8);
    if (nameChanged)
    {
        s.SetProperty(b => b.Name, "foo");
    }
});
```

You can now use regular C# control flow inside the lambda — no expression API needed.

---

### 2. Complex type column names — two sub-changes

**a) Same-named properties are uniquified.** If both `ShippingAddress` and `BillingAddress` have a `Street` property, EF 10 will auto-rename the second to `Street1` instead of silently sharing one column. To keep the old shared column (or pick explicit names):

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Customer>(b =>
{
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.ShippingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("ShippingAddress_Street"));
    b.ComplexProperty(c => c.BillingAddress,
        p => p.Property(a => a.Street).HasColumnName("BillingAddress_Street"));
});
```

**b) Nested complex types now use the full path.** `Order.Payment.BillingAddress.City` was previously mapped to column `BillingAddress_City`; it is now `Payment_BillingAddress_City`. To preserve the old name:

```csharp
modelBuilder.Entity<Order>()
    .ComplexProperty(o => o.Payment)
    .ComplexProperty(p => p.BillingAddress)
    .Property(a => a.City)
    .HasColumnName("BillingAddress_City");
```

If you have an existing database, either add explicit `HasColumnName` calls to match the old names **or** generate a migration and verify the renames are safe.

---

### 3. `IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger` — new `logCommandText` parameter

Every method gained a `string logCommandText` parameter (for redacted SQL logging). Add it to your signatures:

```csharp
public class MyLogger : IRelationalCommandDiagnosticsLogger
{
    public InterceptionResult<DbDataReader> CommandReaderExecuting(
        IRelationalConnection connection,
        DbCommand command,
        DbContext context,
        Guid commandId,
        Guid connectionId,
        DateTimeOffset startTime,
        string logCommandText)   // ← new parameter
    {
        // Use logCommandText for logging (constants may be redacted)
        // Use command.CommandText for the actual executed SQL
    }
}
```

Update **all** methods on the interface (`CommandReaderExecuted`, `CommandScalarExecuting`, etc.) the same way.
